<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 93 / Smith New Court up 400%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Buoyant equity markets in London and overseas helped Smith New Court raise
interim profits to Pounds 31.3m, against Pounds 6.7m, the securities house
disclosed yesterday.
The rise, confirmation of the exceptional profits generated by securities
houses this year, prompted a doubling of the interim dividend to 2p despite
the firm's policy of only adjusting the dividend at the year end. Diluted
earnings per share rose to 25p, against 6.1p. Sir Michael Richardson,
chairman, said the opening few weeks of the second half had shown a
continuation of business levels.
The disclosure of Smith New Court's profits coincided with figures from the
stock exchange showing that November was the busiest month ever for equity
trading in London, with a stock turnover value of Pounds 110.5bn.
Smith New Court's short-term borrowings to finance equity marketmaking
positions were reduced by the firm's access to extra capital. It completed a
Pounds 45.1m rights issue in August to finance expansion.
Mr Michael Marks, chief executive, said that earnings had been evenly split
between marketmaking, its core business from its roots as a jobber, and fees
from corporate and institutional broking into which it had diversified.
He said that more than 60 per cent of revenues had come from overseas,
including broking and marketmaking in Asia Pacific and New York. The firm
saw 'huge opportunities' in India, China and Latin America.
Despite the increase in bonuses expected at securities houses, he said that
expenses from existing staff had 'risen like everything else, but not
exploded'. The company has recruited 60 more staff since last year, bringing
it to 1,360.
Capital and reserves rose from Pounds 92.3m to Pounds 175.3m, helping to
finance the sharp rise in assets held on the balance sheet of Pounds 4.62bn,
against Pounds 2.66bn. Current liabilities to fund the equity book positions
rose from Pounds 4.43bn to Pounds 2.55bn.
The firm expects an appeal in a legal dispute with Citicorp about the sale
of Ferranti to be resolved 'shortly'. It is holding the principal and
interest involved as a result of the original judgement, and could benefit
by Pounds 14m.
Shares closed 11p down at 411p. The two for seven rights issue price in June
was 210p.
Lex, Page 24
</TEXT>
