<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 93 / Stress at work should be seen as safety issue, says report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Stress at work is increasing sharply and should be recognised officially as
a health and safety issue, a report urged yesterday.
Professor Tom Cox of Nottingham University, who prepared the report for the
Health and Safety Executive, said the problem needed government recognition
if employers were to tackle it effectively.
The report, published ahead of HSE guidelines due out next year to help
employers manage stress at work, recommended further research into the
problem, along with training for employers. Recent Manchester University
research showed that 90m working days a year were being lost in the UK
through stress.
The recommendations come at a time when growing numbers of employees are
seeking compensation from their companies for stress-related illnesses.
Several test cases are due to come before the courts. In one, a former City
worker alleges that her 10-15 hour day caused a mental breakdown. Another
employee claims that stress through overwork led to a gynaecological
disorder. In a third case, a junior production manager is claiming that
shortage of staff led to illness through overwork.
According to one of Britain's leading stress counsellors, the problem is
growing more acute as companies emerge from recession with smaller
workforces and leaner managements.
Mr Alistair Anderson, managing director of Personal Performance Consultants
UK, which has contracts with 60 companies covering 130,000 workers
nationwide, said he had noticed a disturbing number of suicides involving
work pressures. 'I believe the demands on the workforce are greater than
they have ever been,' he said.
'Downsizing in companies has meant that often people have been left
ill-equipped and ill-prepared for the job expected of them. That in itself
creates great stress.'
The report by Prof Cox, an occupational psychologist, identified excessive
periods of repetitive work, lack of management support and overdemanding
work schedules as contributory causes of stress.
Added factors were low pay, poor relationships with managers, lack of
variety, shift working, long hours, job insecurity and conflicting demands
of work and home.
</TEXT>
