<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There must be something pretty funny about Ben Elton because some of us
continue to laugh even though his obsessive political correctness makes us
groan. It will be interesting to see whether his own adaptation of his own
book, Stark, is as funny as his stand-up act. Elton himself stars as an
English writer in Australia at a time when the earth is being asphyxiated by
industrial pollution (9.25 BBC2).
Elsewhere the schedules are dominated by state terrorism. Salman Rushdie
introduces Shooting The Writer. Six of Algeria's intelligentsia have been
assassinated this year, and Islamic terrorists have now issued an ultimatum
to the 100,000 foreigners in the country: leave or become targets (8.00
BBC2). In Human Rights, Human Wrongs Rushdie describes the way hundreds of
thousands of families have been destroyed in Bosnia-Herzegovina in 'ethnic
cleansing' (8.50 BBC2).
In his BBC1 series States Of Terror, Peter Taylor investigates US reactions
to the suicide attacks on Americans in Beirut in the early 1980s (9.30).
