<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 93 / Budgets vary for health authorities
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Health authority budgets in England are to rise by an average of 5.33 per
cent next year, Mrs Virginia Bottomley, health secretary, announced
yesterday.
All 14 health regions will receive a real-terms increase but they will range
from more than 2 per cent to as low as 0.7 per cent, particularly in London
areas of falling population.
Doctors in the north-west will get an increase of more than 10 per cent in
real terms while those in East Anglia, Wessex, South Western and North-West
Thames will be given a standstill budget.
