FT  08 DEC 93 / Equality chief to quit a year early
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ms Valerie Amos, chief executive of the Equal Opportunity Commission, is
leaving her job a year before the end of her contract to pursue other
interests.
Ms Amos, who came to the job four years ago from local government, succeeded
in putting the commission on a more structured footing with stronger
management and making it more accessible to grassroots organisations and
ethnic minorities.
She is understood, however, to have some difficulty developing a strong
personal relationship with Ms Kamlesh Bahl who took over the commission's
chair in June.
Ms Amos resigned the post almost a month ago. No announcement was made,
although a short briefing was prepared in the event of possible press
inquiries.
Ms Bahl, who worked as a lawyer in industry before tasking up her
appointment, said in the briefing that Ms Amos had worked with 'great
dedication and loyalty to bring about many changes for the EOC'.
Ms Amos was yesterday anxious to play down suggestions that a personality
clash had been a key factor in her decision to leave. 'That kind of thing is
always said when there is a new chair. Kamlesh and I have worked very well
together. I wouldn't describe our working relationship as a difficult one.'
