<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 93 / Abbey trims mortgage rates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Abbey National, the UK's second-largest mortgage lender, yesterday cut its
mortgage rates by 0.25 percentage points to a range between 7.54 and 7.74
per cent.
It said that the reduction - less than that announced by Halifax Building
Society on Monday - reflected the fact that falling interest rates were bad
news for savers.
Alliance &amp; Leicester, the fourth-largest society, followed Halifax, the
largest, by announcing a cut of 0.35 percentage points to 7.64 per cent in
its variable rate.
Other main lenders joining Abbey in the smaller cut of 0.25 points were
Leeds Permanent, the fifth-largest society, and Midland Bank. The series of
cuts has been triggered by a pre-Budget 0.5 percentage point reduction in
base rates.
The new rates will be available immediately to new borrowers, and to
existing borrowers from January.
Mr Chris Chadwick, Leeds executive director, echoed the warning from other
societies that if the government subsidised its savings products to attract
investors, then societies might not be able to pass on to borrowers further
cuts in interest rates. He said: 'Over-aggressive pricing on national
savings will impact on lenders' ability to maintain current rates or reduce
them any further.'
Many mortgage lenders have not announced new rates for savers, but are
likely to do so before the end of the month.
</TEXT>
