FT  08 DEC 93 / Heseltine boosts business-aid cash
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary, yesterday announced
a number of initiatives to help industry and small businesses.
He used his speech in the final day of the Budget debate in the Commons to
announce an increase from Pounds 14m to Pounds 17m in start-up funding for
Business Link outlets.
The outlets are designed to bring together under one roof most of the
services provided by training and enterprise councils, chambers of commerce,
local authorities, enterprise agencies, and other private-sector
organisations.
The first of a planned national network have opened in Birmingham,
Leicester, and Congleton in Cheshire. Mr Heseltine said Tecs - which deliver
government training schemes in England and Wales - 'have a key strategic
role in organising the provision of business support services'.
Tecs' budgets for services to small businesses - most of which will be taken
into Business Link outlets - is to increase slightly to Pounds 33m.
Mr Heseltine also announced an environmental technology best-practice
programme, worth Pounds 16m, and a new Link programme on surface
engineering.
Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary, said spending by Mr
Heseltine's department would drop by some 12 per cent in real terms in the
next three years, and this reflected the falling investment in Britain's
manufacturing industry.
'Out of 18 spending departments, the DTI is 17th,' said Mr Cook. 'Britain
provides less support to industry than any other European country.'
