<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 93 / Fiasco of Sundays may have had its chips / Review of the
shop-hours options open to MPs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Sunday trading bill was supposed to be one of the most contentious
pieces of legislation to come before the Commons in the current session.
Tempers were expected to run so high that the government, bruised by a
successful backbench revolt on the issue in 1986, allowed a free vote.
It has not happened. The bill passed its second reading by a huge majority
after a polite debate last week and has almost disappeared from view, buried
by controversy over the Budget and the Ulster peace talks.
That may change today when MPs debate the core of the bill - three options
put forward by retailing and religious pressure groups to reform the widely
ignored 1950 Shops Act. The options are:
Complete de-regulation, bringing England and Wales into line with Scotland,
favoured by the Conservative right and backed by the prime minister, the
home secretary and a majority of the cabinet.
Unrestricted trading for small shops, with a six-hour limit on larger
stores. This was drafted by the Shopping Hours Reform Council, which
represents big chains such as Tesco that already open on Sundays, in
defiance of the law. Unregulated opening for most small shops, DIY stores
and garden centres, and unregulated opening for four Sundays before
Christmas. This is backed by the Keep Sunday Special (KSS) campaign, an
alliance of small retailers and sabbatarians, and some big stores, including
Marks and Spencer and John Lewis.
There is broad agreement that the 1950 act is well past its sell-by date.
For example, fish and chips may be sold at a take-away outlet other than a
fish and chip shop, while fish and chip shops can sell any takeaway food
other than fish and chips.
But there is no consensus on which option, if any, will win. The least
likely outcome is de-regulation, which is opposed by a big majority on the
opposition benches. It would have to attract the votes of virtually all
Conservative MPs to succeed.
That is unlikely because of the strength of support among traditionalist
Conservatives for the KSS option. The KSS group is worried, however, by the
defection of Usdaw, the shopworkers' union, once a strong supporter but now
backing the six-hours option.
The union's decision has split its 12 sponsored Labour MPs, some of whom
will stand by KSS. But many Labour MPs are likely to follow the union into
the six-hour lobby, which also has the support of the TGWU, the other union
representing shopworkers.
Both sides claim the support of a majority of MPs. But the first option to
attract a majority of votes cast will win, which means that the decision
might hinge on the order in which the speaker calls the options.
The provisional order - de-regulation, KSS, six-hours - appears to favour
the last option, if only because MPs are likely to want to resolve the issue
if the other two options have been defeated.
Further complicating the issue, Sir Peter Emery, a Conservative backbencher,
has tabled a series of amendments which would prevent trading on Sunday
mornings. The government says it is neutral on this approach.
It is possible that no option will win a majority. If that happens the
government will probably bring the least unpopular option back to the
Commons after giving MPs a few weeks to mull over the chaos they will have
caused. But it is a scenario which gives ministers nightmares.
</TEXT>
