<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 93 / W Midland engineers see orders decline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The flow of orders to the west Midlands engineering industry from both home
and overseas has slowed down in the past three months and a declining
proportion of companies expect order books to grow in the next three months.
The latest survey of business trends, conducted by the Engineering Employers
Federation West Midlands just before the Budget and covering 494 companies,
demonstrates the shallowness of economic recovery and offers an antidote to
optimism.
Recent regional surveys had suggested that the west Midlands, with its
dependence on manufacturing, would be one of the regions to emerge from
recession most quickly.
Engineering employers reported yesterday that the proportion of companies
experiencing an increase in domestic orders fell to 37 per cent in November
from 46 per cent in May. Those experiencing a rise in export orders fell to
22 per cent from 27 per cent.
Twenty one per cent of companies expect a fall in capacity utilisation over
the next three months.
</TEXT>
