FT  08 DEC 93 / Talks begin on airways dispute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The UK and US governments yesterday started a new round of talks in London
to try to resolve their dispute over transatlantic air services, Paul Betts
writes.
The UK has already warned Washington it would limit US airline services to
London's Heathrow Airport if the Washington administration sought to curtail
the rights of British Airways in the US.
Mr Lawrence Nagin, an executive vice-president of United Airlines, one of
the big three US carriers, said that a trade war between the two countries
would ultimately hit the consumer hardest because of the risk of fewer
transatlantic services.
The US will be pressing the UK government to grant US carriers more access
into Heathrow airport. The UK is seeking an easing in US regulations on
foreign ownership of US carriers.
