<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 93 / Schools face crackdown on teaching hours
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Schools in England and Wales will have to publish details of the number of
hours spent teaching each day, after the first annual report of Ofsted, the
school inspection service, called for an urgent inquiry into the length of
the school day.
The Department for Education made clear that it was planning action on the
length of school days after a 20 per cent variation in the total time
schools spend teaching was revealed. Mr John Patten, education secretary,
said the variation was 'unacceptably wide'. He added: 'Parents must wonder
how one school can offer up to a day a week more teaching than another, and
what effect this has. I certainly do.'
The report said bullying was a problem in every school inspected, and found
'an urgent need for improvement of educational management and leadership,
especially in matching resources to priorities'.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, announced the plan to add more
information to the league tables published on schools each year.
Professor Stewart Sutherland, chief inspector of schools, said the
variation, from more than 25 hours tuition each week to less than 20 hours,
was equivalent to a whole year's extra teaching at some schools over five
years.
Teachers' unions reacted with alarm. Mr Nigel de Gruchy, general secretary
of the NASUWT union, said the report was an 'implicit suggestion that the
school day should be lengthened'. It would meet 'outright opposition from
teachers faced with increased workload and a possible pay freeze'.
The report found that in all schools most lessons were at least
satisfactory. However, 30 per cent of lessons for children between eight and
11 were unsatisfactory while only 15 per cent of classes for
post-16-year-olds were unsatisfactory.
Ofsted added that there was a 'stubborn percentage of unsatisfactory
teaching' and a 'small proportion' which was 'downright poor'.
Good teaching standards had a 'direct correlation' with successful academic
results, but there was evidence that poor teaching was concentrated in inner
cities.
Prof Sutherland said: 'Sadly, the incidence of such teaching is often
greater in schools serving pupils and parents in urban areas with high
levels of social and economic disadvantage. We cannot be satisfied until we
record improvements for all children, regardless of back-ground.'
Ofsted is also to start a full investigation of the sharp drop in popularity
of mathematics and science courses compared with arts subjects. Prof
Sutherland said: 'There is no doubt about the trend - the overall number of
students taking A-levels is increasing while the proportion taking science
and mathematics is declining.'
He said there was a growing trend for teachers to have to teach areas of
science and mathematics with which they were not familiar, but would not
speculate further on the reasons behind the trend.
</TEXT>
