<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 93 / Ivory Coast left an explosive legacy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LESLIE CRAWFORD, Africa Correspondent, and AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
President Felix Houphouet-Boigny of the Ivory Coast, Africa's longest
serving leader, died yesterday at the age of 88. He was the only leader the
country had known since independence from France in 1960.
The speaker of parliament, Mr Henri Konan Bedie, subsequently announced that
he had become president, sparking a struggle for the succession with the
prime minister, Mr Alassane Ouattara.
Whether out of vanity or superstition, Mr Houphouet-Boigny had refused to
groom an heir. 'An African chief never names his successor,' he once said,
and the subject became taboo.
In the past few days a succession crisis had developed. Mr Konan Bedie's
constitutional claim to the presidency, as parliamentary speaker, was
strongly contested by supporters of the prime minister, and by opposition
leaders.
Ivorians had been expecting the death of the president, who was stricken by
prostate cancer and had not been seen in public after he flew home from
Europe in a hospital aircraft on November 19. He stayed in his palace in the
town of Yamoussoukro, his birthplace.
The succession row centred on Article 11 of the constitution, which states
that the parliamentary speaker takes over at the president's death, ruling
until the next elections. But Mr Ouattara's supporters have been campaigning
for round-table talks to agree an interim authority until elections.
Although Mr Konan Bedie, a career politician from the president's Baoule
tribe, has the strongest claim to the presidency, Mr Ouattara, a former
director of the International Monetary Fund, enjoys a more solid reputation.
Mr Ouattara is nominally in charge of a government that has drifted for most
of this year.
Under Mr Houphouet-Boigny, Ivory Coast became the world's leading cocoa
producer and third coffee exporter. But it was too dependent on fluctuating
commodity prices and recent years have seen unemployment, crime and
corruption soar.
Policies that could arrest the Ivory Coast's economic decline have not been
forthcoming. France, which has paid the country's annual Dollars 350m
(Pounds 250m) debt-servicing bill to the World Bank since 1992, is
threatening to withdraw its support at the end of the year. The country
cannot service its Dollars 17.3bn foreign debt by itself.
The collapse of commodity prices has impoverished the country. The World
Bank estimates per capita incomes have plunged by 25 per cent since 1987.
'It is a decline comparable only to the hardships suffered in the Soviet
Union,' says a World Bank economist, 'without safety nets or programmes for
the poor.'
In the minds of many Ivorians, the country's economic malaise became fused
with the president's declining health.
Ivorians fear there is no one of Houphouet-Boigny's stature to rein in
ethnic and social tensions which threaten West Africa's most stable regime.
'Houphouet's legacy is crumbling,' says Mr Laurent Gbagbo, leader of the
largest opposition party, the Front Populaire Ivoirien. 'The ruling party is
tearing itself apart in the leadership struggle; the government is bankrupt;
civil servants are on strike. Our task today is to rebuild this crumbling
edifice together.'
So far, Mr Gbagbo's message has fallen on deaf ears. Racist overtones have
crept into the fray. Newspapers backing Mr Konan Bedie denounce Mr Ouattara
as a 'foreigner' because he was educated in Burkina Faso and the US.
Newspapers behind the prime minister attack the Konan Bedie camp as
'fascists'.
Underlying the concerns of many diplomats is the fear that if the
politicians cannot agree among themselves, the military will take over.
Mr Konan Bedie, 59, enjoys the backing of France, and the US, where he
served as a young ambassador after independence. His only career setback was
in 1977 when he was removed from overall charge of the Ivorian economy and
sent into exile as an adviser to the World Bank in Washington.
At the time, Mr Konan Bedie had presided for 11 years over an economy that
enjoyed steady growth. Mr Houphouet-Boigny sacked him and other ministers
after financial scandals. But in 1980 he was back, elected as parliamentary
speaker.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>CIZ  Ivory Coast, Africa.
</CN>
