<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 93 / Brazil plans to bring in a new currency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRASILIA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Brazil yesterday announced a package of measures, including eventual
introduction of a new currency, to tackle the country's soaring inflation
rate of about 2,000 per cent a year.
The package, the seventh stabilisation attempt since 1986, will be
introduced gradually and will probably not take full effect until after the
government's term runs out next year.
It won cautious backing from the government's coalition partners and
economists because the measures first tackle Brazil's budget deficit, seen
as the main cause of inflation, and do not include 'shock' measures like
price freezes which have failed in the past, even if initially successful.
But several of the measures still need approval from Congress, which has
been paralysed by a corruption scandal tainting many of its members.
Proposed cuts in transfers to states and municipalities will also antagonise
Brazil's powerful state governors.
The government admits approval of the package may be difficult but hopes
that by explaining the measures in advance the country will realise the
severity of the problems.
It fears that, without the package, inflation will accelerate ahead of next
year's presidential and congressional elections. 'Economic policy will then
have to be either highly recessionary and politically unsustainable, or you
will have hyperinflation,' according to Mr Winston Fritsch, economic policy
secretary.
The first stage of the package, announced in general terms last week, is
built into next year's budget and calls for spending cuts and
revenue-raising measures to wipe out a projected deficit of Dollars 22.2bn.
The cuts include a set-aside of 15 per cent of the transfers made from the
central government to states and municipalities, to save Dollars 5.6bn.
There is also a 5 per cent increase in all federal taxes, to take the top
income tax rate from 25 per cent to 26.25 per cent, to raise Dollars 3.7bn.
Congress has to approve the budget and several constitutional amendments to
cover areas such as the 15 per cent set-aside, as well as longer-term
measures to solve a deficit in the social security system.
Mr Fernando Henrique Cardoso, finance minister, also announced he would
support a number of measures designed to 'modernise the economy'. These
included the ending of the state monopoly on telecommunications and the
cancellation of a ban on the involvement of foreign controlled companies in
mineral extraction.
These areas are politically sensitive, and can only be approved through a
constitutional revision which is under way. Mr Cardoso was less specific
about the even more sensitive monopoly enjoyed by state oil company
Petrobras.
If the first stage of the package is approved, a new index to measure
inflation daily will be introduced. Almost all government revenues and many
private sector prices are at present adjusted in line with past inflation
measures, which often adds to inflationary expectations.
The new index could eventually be linked to the US dollar or a basket of
currencies and adjusted daily, as happens with the central bank adjusting
the exchange rate. The index would then become a new currency unit, backed
by Brazil's foreign currency reserves of over Dollars 20bn and the central
bank would be given more autonomy over monetary emission.
The new index, called the Unidade Real de Valor or unit of real value, is
partly designed to erase inflationary expectations which have dogged
previous currencies.
By shortening the period of price indexation and making index-linked
contracts forward-looking, past inflation would no longer contaminate the
new currency, the government hopes.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>BRZ  Brazil, South America.
