<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Bernard Tapie, the businessman-turned-politician, is expected to face
prosecution on financial irregularity charges after the French national
assembly lifted his parliamentary immunity.
The 432-72 vote came in response to a judge's request to investigate alleged
misuse of corporate funds from Testut, a small near-bankrupt manufacturer of
weighing scales controlled by Bernard Tapie Finance.
The company has been used to extend loans to Olympique-Marseille, the
football club which Mr Tapie also controls, to buy football stars.
In a separate investigation, another judge has applied to parliament to lift
Mr Tapie's immunity from facing charges of bribing another soccer team to
lose to O-M last May.
Appealing to fellow deputies, Mr Tapie said yesterday: 'This assembly is
asked to cast the first stone at me. And this will allow others to cast
bigger, heavier stones perhaps at me, but perhaps they will also hit some of
you.'
Several, mostly Socialist deputies, have been implicated in alleged illegal
funding of political parties by businessmen seeking public contracts.
