<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 93 / News Corp abandons 'super' share plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
News Corporation, the Australian media and film company headed by Mr Rupert
Murdoch, last night withdrew its controversial plan to issue shares with
'super' voting rights to existing shareholders.
The plan, announced in October, created concern in Australia, where
differental voting rights are not currently permitted. Critics saw it as a
means by which the Murdoch family interests could establish an entrenched
controlling position at News Corporation.
The Murdoch family owns about one-third of News' shares, but its stake has
slipped as the company has been obliged to issue new equity to fund
acquisitions and pay down debt. The proposed scheme would have allowed the
family to stabilise its interest - and even increase it via further
purchases of 'super' shares, which provide multiple voting rights - while
the company could have continued to issue ordinary shares.
Mr Murdoch acknowleged that Australian authorities were unlikely to decide
on the scheme for many months. The News board had decided at a meeting in
London to withdraw the plan.
</TEXT>
