<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 93 / Options for divorce reform put forward
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Quick, no-fault divorce after a year's separation, where partners do not
have to make any accusations, was one of the options for divorce law reform
outlined yesterday in a government green paper.
Lord Mackay, the Lord Chancellor, launching the consultation document, said
he was aiming for a system which was 'better at identifying savable
marriages'.
Couples should be encouraged to face the consequences of divorce before
ending their marriages. But where divorce was unavoidable the system should
minimise the bitterness and conflict between parties and reduce the trauma
for children, he said.
About 75 per cent of the 150,000 divorces a year in England and Wales are
granted for adultery or unreasonable behaviour. The green paper suggests a
one-year 'cooling-off' period before divorce is granted on these grounds.
</TEXT>
