FT  07 DEC 93 / Rover to switch staff to assembly line work
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Rover Group, the motor vehicles subsidiary of British Aerospace, is seeking
to transfer up to 1,000 indirect production workers and white-collar staff
on to direct assembly line production work next year, Kevin Done writes.
Mr John Towers, Rover Group managing director, has written to indirect
production workers and staff in the search for volunteers to switch to
direct jobs on the assembly lines in order to cope with an expected increase
of more than 10 per cent in output in 1994.
The company said that it was seeking to raise output without making any
significant increase in the total workforce of about 33,000.
Rover said that it had surplus indirect production workers in areas such as
logistics, materials handling and maintenance, and it was chiefly seeking
volunteers among these indirect workers to transfer to direct jobs on the
assembly lines or in engine and transmission assembly and body pressings.
