FT  07 DEC 93 / Haitian premier insists on quitting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   Washington
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Robert Malval said yesterday that he still planned to resign as Haiti's
prime minister on December 15, despite US pressure to remain in office, but
would continue as acting prime minister until a compromise successor could
be found, George Graham reports from Washington.
'According to law, I have to stay as acting prime minister until a successor
is named,' he said, after talks in Washington with Father Jean-Bertrand
Aristide, the Haitian president, who was ousted two years ago by a military
coup.
Mr Malval had intended to serve as temporary prime minister to oversee
Father Aristide's return to Haiti, set for last October but not yet
effected.
However, the premier's position has been uncertain, amid much violence in
Haiti, local military leaders having reneged on their agreement to this
UN-brokered plan.
