FT  07 DEC 93 / EU agrees research share-out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The European Union agreed yesterday how to distribute research funds in the
next five years, with information and communications technologies receiving
the most, Reuter reports from Brussels.
The research ministers' decisions were conditional on agreeing an overall
budget, EC officials said. The ministers were also still discussing how to
reform the EC's Joint Research Centre.
The European Commission has proposed spending Ecu13.1bn (Pounds 10bn) on the
so-called 1994-98 Fourth Framework Programme, which will channel money to
companies and research institutes across Europe. But Britain, France and
Germany, the biggest contributors to the research budget, say that is too
high.
The ministers agreed information and communications technologies should get
28.2 per cent of the budget; energy 18.15 per cent, industrial technologies
16 per cent; and biotechnology and other life sciences 13.1 per cent.
