<DATE>931207
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 93 / London Stock Exchange: Takeover activity features steady
session - Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND, UK Stock Market Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Speculative activity in the television and brewery sectors bore witness
yesterday to the positive mood of the UK stock market. Across the broad
range of leading stocks, profit-takers were comfortably balanced by new
buyers and share prices closed firmly. The pace was erratic, with the stock
index futures leading the activity.
Firmness in UK government bonds ahead of tomorrow's auction of Pounds 3bn of
10-year gilts, in the last bond sale of the year, encouraged equities,
offsetting suggestions in some quarters that base rate cuts might be
delayed. A good start by US Federal bonds, accompanied by an early advance
of 11 Dow points on Wall Street, encouraged London.
The FT-SE 100 Index finished 3.1 up at a new closing peak of 3,237.3, having
moved between 3,243.6 and 3,224.3 during the session. The FT-SE Mid 250
Index, which took in activity in the television stocks in the wake of
Granada's Pounds 600m bid for LWT Holdings, shaded down by 0.7 to 3,565.8.
The Granada bid, while not unexpected, set the Television sector alight.
Analysts quickly divided into those believing a rival bidder might appear
and those convinced that Granada could be induced to pay a slightly higher
price for LWT.
Elsewhere, it was mostly company trading statements that provided the
highlights. Saatchi &amp; Saatchi, Scottish and Newcastle, Airtours and National
Home Loans all stood out under this heading.
Seaq volume remained high at 601.9m shares against 749.2m on Friday when
retail business of Pounds 1.88bn indicated the continued vigour of the UK
stock market's reponse to last week's Budget from Mr Kenneth Clarke, the
chancellor of the exchequer.
With little data on the domestic economy due this month, attention has
turned again to the US, where reports on producer and consumer prices will
be published this week. Nervousness regarding the Japanese stock market also
resurfaced, with equities opening lower in London yesterday after the
setback in Tokyo.
The best performances came again from the banks, where the clearers
continued to see benefits ahead for their bad debt lists from further falls
in UK base rates, while the merchant banks counted the profits made in such
active securities markets. Towards the close, the stock market have regained
its confidence that base rates rates will be cut again in the new year,
encouraged by the announcement of lower mortgage rates by one of Britain's
leading home loan groups. But insurance stocks gave back some of the gains
achieved following an unexpectedly benign Budget.
There were ready buyers across the range of consumer issues, with food
retailers, stores and hotels firm. Dividend prospects spurred strong gains
among the utilities.
The clouds hanging over crude oil prices kept the big oil stocks subdued
throughout the session, and signs of renewed pressure from New York left the
sector looking weaker in the final minutes of the trading session.
The blue chip manufacturing issues moved narrowly around overnight levels,
the pharmaceuticals lacking a lead from New York and many other big names
shying away from the firmness in sterling which offers little help to export
prospects. Overall, however, market strategists were confident that the
stock market has retained the confidence with which the Budget was greeted
last week.
</TEXT>
