<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 93 / London Stock Exchange: Equity Futures and Options Trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Dealers in the London derivatives market began to concentrate on the
exceptionally high level of open interest in Footsie futures as activity
drifted back to pre-Budget levels yesterday, writes Peter John.
By the close of business, the series in the FT-SE 100 Index which expires at
the end of next week still had open interest above 50,000 lots. That figure
represents the number of contracts bought as well as the number of contracts
sold. Some traders are concerned that those with long positions, mostly
investment funds and asset allocaters, might find it diff-icult to close out
their positions over the next eight trading days.
Many of the contracts will be rolled out to the next contract, which expires
in March. For the rest, the longs - ie buyers - will need to find a willing
seller. There is a feeling that because of exceptional profits made this
year and over the life of the December contract some of the shorts, who are
mainly marketmakers arbitraging between the level of the futures contract
and the level of the market, might prefer to let positions expire thus
taking the cash but creating an imbalance in the market.
The December contract opened at 3,252 and saw some if its unusually high
premium to cash narrow slightly before hitting 3,251, by the official close.
At that level however it still showed a premium of 13 in contrast to a fair
value estimate of zero.
Options turnover returned to a desultory level of 23,102 with stock options
activity headed by Lasmo as one investor sold 500 February calls and bought
500 May calls to roll forward the investment.
</TEXT>
