<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 93 / International Company News: Bronfmans sell Seagram shares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Canadian members of the Bronfman family, through the Charles Bronfman
trust, have sold 3.7m Seagram shares on the New York stock market for nearly
USDollars 100m.
The sale reduces the trust's holding from 62m shares to 58m shares or almost
16 per cent. Three Bronfman family trusts control Seagram, one of the
world's top drinks groups.
Mr Michel Boucher, vice-president of Claridge, the Montreal-based holding
company for the Charles Bronfman group, said the sale was 'part of the
family's financial planning'.
The shares included a block of 3.28m cross-traded by Goldman Sachs
yesterday. Mr Boucher said he was unaware of the buyers of the Seagram
block. Seagram shares fell about 3 per cent following the block trade.
The stock sale came several days after Seagram reported a third-quarter loss
of 27 US cents a share due to a 64 cents special charge, Seagram's share of
a USDollars 1.3bn write-down by Du Pont. Seagram holds 24.3 per cent of the
chemicals giant.
In New York, Seagram spokesman Mr Chris Tofalli said the sale was made for
personal reasons. 'It happens from time to time but such sales are not that
frequent.'
Charles Bronfman is co-chairman of Seagram. His elder brother, Edgar, of New
York, is chairman and his son, Edgar Bronfman Jr, took over as Seagram
president several years ago to reorganise the worldwide group.
