<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 93 / Saatchi &amp; Saatchi shares fall after profit warning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Saatchi &amp; Saatchi, the heavily-indebted advertising group, fell by
23p to 157p yesterday following a profits warning.
The loss of two large accounts in the US, worth Pounds 30m in revenue for
1994, plus pessimism about client spending, will lead to more redundancies.
An extra Pounds 10m of severance costs in 1993 comes on top of the
previously-expected Pounds 5m, said the group.
Saatchi is to vacate its offices in Berkeley Square, in the West End of
London, which will save Pounds 1.2m annually from 1994.
Last week the group announced that Mr Charles Saatchi, who has played little
part in the day-to-day running of the business, would step down as a
director. He will draw a salary of Pounds 312,500 but has given up his
entitlement to twice that.
Analysts had been forecasting pre-tax profits for 1993 of between Pounds 24m
and Pounds 29m. Mr Neil Blackley, of Goldman Sachs, who had been forecasting
Pounds 25m, said Pounds 19m was now more likely. The 1993 results are due in
March. His forecast for 1994 is likely to be revised downwards from Pounds
42m to Pounds 35m.
Mr Blackley said yesterday: 'Everyone loses business. The problem is they
haven't been winning any. It's like a football game. You're always going to
let a few goals in but you've got to keep scoring more than you let in.
That's what Saatchi has not been achieving.'
The 1992 results, excluding the Pounds 600m of goodwill written off by the
group, showed underlying pre-tax profits of Pounds 18.9m. No dividend was
paid, but Mr Charles Scott, who took over as chief executive in April, has
committed the group to paying a dividend in 1994.
The two large accounts lost in the US were from Chrysler, the carmaker, and
Helene Curtis, the haircare products company. The group has also taken
soundings among its 13,000 clients and is pessimistic about spending on
advertising for 1994, particularly in continental Europe and in the US.
Saatchi is pitching for several large accounts, including Burger King, the
hamburger chain.
The warning was announced in New York at the Paine Webber media conference,
attended by leading industry figures.
Market, Page 38
</TEXT>
