<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
To the generation of journalists now in middle age, Robert Fisk is what
James Cameron was to the previous generation: a man who seems to have been
in every major war zone for a couple of decades, yet who writes about war
without any of the gung-ho relish common among war reporters.
How he has survived so long on so many fronts is a mystery, though last time
we met he gave a hint. You could always tell the new boys when you came
under heavy attack, he said, they dived for cover the moment they heard the
explosions, but the old hands had gone down a split second sooner, as they
felt the reverberation through the air. Today he begins a three part series
on Islamic fundamentalism, From Beirut To Bosnia (9.00 C4).
There seem to be lots of serious programmes tonight. Assignment (7.35 BBC2)
reports on China's 'economic miracle' but that is followed by Human Rights,
Human Wrongs which includes an assertion from Helen Suzman that torture is
now endemic in China (8.20 BBC2).
</TEXT>
